<Document>
<name>East Java — Bromo to Ijen to Banyuwangi</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>East Java — Bromo to Ijen to Banyuwangi</h2><p><i>East Java, Indonesia · Probolinggo to Banyuwangi via Bromo and Ijen</i></p><p><b>Two of Indonesia's most extraordinary volcanoes in 250 km — a smoking caldera and an electric-blue acid lake.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>238 km (148 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>2–3 days minimum</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>May–October dry season (volcanoes are clearer; access roads passable)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Mountain weather closes summit views; sulfuric gases at Ijen require a mask; Bromo and Ijen both involve pre-dawn starts; volcanic eruption alerts can close access at any time</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>458</td></tr></table><hr><p>Java has 45 active volcanoes — the most of any island on Earth. This drive samples two of the strangest. Mount Bromo sits inside the 10 km-wide Tengger caldera with a sand sea around its base; the sunrise viewpoints from Penanjakan ridge above show Bromo's smoking cone, the higher Mount Semeru behind it (Java's tallest, 3,676 m, smoking on a 20-minute schedule), and the mist-filled crater floor below. From Bromo the road traces south coast roads east to Banyuwangi. Above Banyuwangi rises Ijen, whose 200 m-deep crater holds the world's largest acid lake (turquoise blue, pH ~0.5, undrinkable) and at night burns with electric-blue flames where sulfur gas combusts on contact with air. Sulfur miners walk down into the crater nightly carrying 70 kg loads of yellow rock on their shoulders. From Banyuwangi a ferry crosses to Bali.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Cemoro Lawang</b> — Village clinging to the outer rim of the Tengger caldera. Most accommodations here. From the village edge you look down on the sea of sand and the smoking cone.</li><li><b>Mount Bromo</b> — Active 2,329 m cone in the Tengger sand sea. Walk across the sand at dawn, climb 250 stairs to the rim, look in. Sulfuric. The Tenggerese (Hindu Javanese) make annual offerings of livestock and produce thrown into the crater.</li><li><b>Penanjakan viewpoint</b> — 2,770 m. The classic Bromo sunrise photograph spot — Bromo, Batok, and Semeru in alignment as light hits them. 4WD jeep tours leave Cemoro Lawang at 3:30 AM.</li><li><b>Paltuding</b> — Ijen trailhead (1,850 m). Most hikers leave at midnight to reach the rim at 3 AM for the blue flame. 3 km up; ~1.5 hr at hiking pace; gas masks essential at the rim.</li><li><b>Kawah Ijen</b> — 1 km-wide crater holding the world's largest acidic lake. Sulfur miners descend nightly to break yellow rock at the lake's edge — the toughest job in Indonesia, paid by the kilogram. Blue flames are pure burning sulfur gas.</li><li><b>Ketapang ferry</b> — Hourly car ferry to Gilimanuk on Bali — 30-minute crossing of the Bali Strait. Crocodile-shaped Bali outline visible on a clear day.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
