<Folder><name>Scenic Points</name><Placemark><name>Cemoro Lawang</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[Village clinging to the outer rim of the Tengger caldera. Most accommodations here. From the village edge you look down on the sea of sand and the smoking cone.]]></description><Point><coordinates>112.952200,-7.913600,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Mount Bromo</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[Active 2,329 m cone in the Tengger sand sea. Walk across the sand at dawn, climb 250 stairs to the rim, look in. Sulfuric. The Tenggerese (Hindu Javanese) make annual offerings of livestock and produce thrown into the crater.]]></description><Point><coordinates>112.952800,-7.942500,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Penanjakan viewpoint</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[2,770 m. The classic Bromo sunrise photograph spot — Bromo, Batok, and Semeru in alignment as light hits them. 4WD jeep tours leave Cemoro Lawang at 3:30 AM.]]></description><Point><coordinates>112.947200,-7.886700,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Paltuding</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[Ijen trailhead (1,850 m). Most hikers leave at midnight to reach the rim at 3 AM for the blue flame. 3 km up; ~1.5 hr at hiking pace; gas masks essential at the rim.]]></description><Point><coordinates>114.241700,-8.058100,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Kawah Ijen</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[1 km-wide crater holding the world's largest acidic lake. Sulfur miners descend nightly to break yellow rock at the lake's edge — the toughest job in Indonesia, paid by the kilogram. Blue flames are pure burning sulfur gas.]]></description><Point><coordinates>114.242500,-8.060000,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Ketapang ferry</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[Hourly car ferry to Gilimanuk on Bali — 30-minute crossing of the Bali Strait. Crocodile-shaped Bali outline visible on a clear day.]]></description><Point><coordinates>114.411100,-8.142800,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark></Folder>
</Document></kml>
